# Tell, Don't Ask

**Tell:** call an intent method (`publish`, `approveProposal`, `cancel`) that owns the decision and state change.

**Don't ask:** avoid `if (entity.getStatus() == X) { entity.setStatus(Y); … }` spread across callers — that leaks invariants and duplicates business rules.

Naming must follow [domain-model.mdc](domain-model.mdc) ubiquitous language. See also [contraponto-law-of-demeter.mdc](contraponto-law-of-demeter.mdc).

## Layers

```
*Endpoint  →  tell  →  *Service  →  tell  →  Entity / *Repository
```

- **Endpoint:** parse input, authorize, then **one** service call — no business branching on entity getters.
- **Service:** orchestrate workflows; when logic depends on entity state **and** mutation, expose a single intent method (e.g. `PostPublicationService.publish(Post)`).
- **Entity:** prefer domain verbs when adding or changing invariants (`approve()`, `reject()`); keep getters for reads and templates.

## Violations vs fixes

```java
// ❌ Caller owns the state machine
if (proposal.getStatus() != ProposalStatus.PENDING) {
    throw new BadRequestException("Proposal is not pending.");
}
proposal.setStatus(ProposalStatus.APPROVED);
proposal.setResolvedAt(now);

// ✅ Entity or service owns the transition
proposal.approve(owner);
// or highlightService.approveProposal(...) when orchestration spans repos/events
```

```java
// ❌ Scattered publish logic
if (!post.isPublished()) { post.setPublished(true); /* … */ }

// ✅
postPublicationService.publish(post);
```

```java
// ❌ Same guard duplicated in many callers
if (!post.isPublished() || post.getLivePublication() == null) { … }

// ✅ One place
post.requirePublished(); // or postPublicationService.ensureReadableByReader(post)
```

## Allowed "ask"

- **Read-only / presentation:** view models, row DTOs, RSS metadata (`post.isPublished()` for display).
- **Authorization:** `*Access` classes (`UserAccess.canManageUsers`) — their job is to answer capability questions.
- **Persistence queries:** repository Criteria/JPQL filters (`WHERE published = true`).
- **Boundary guards** that immediately delegate: `if (!post.isPublished()) return notFound();` then call a service — acceptable at the HTTP edge; prefer a single service method when the guard repeats.

## Pragmatic guidance

- **Do not** mandate a big-bang refactor of anemic JPA entities (e.g. `Post` with `setPublished`).
- **Do** apply Tell, Don't Ask on **new or touched** behavior: new transitions, new endpoints, duplicated `if (getStatus())` blocks.
- When touching legacy ask-then-set code, **consolidate** into the nearest `*Service` or entity method in the same change (same spirit as [contraponto-no-method-bypass-allowed.mdc](contraponto-no-method-bypass-allowed.mdc)).

## Never

- Add business rules in endpoints that belong in a service or entity.
- Expose mutable state (`setStatus`, `setPublished`) from new code when an intent method would enforce invariants.
- Copy the same state-check + mutation block into a second caller — extract a tell method instead.
